                            <comment id="311339" author="adilger" created="Thu, 26 Aug 2021 20:23:17 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1 on master &lt;a href=&quot;https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sets/220ac885-cdcd-42f9-bd09-3c1160c27945&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sets/220ac885-cdcd-42f9-bd09-3c1160c27945&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The original commit adding test_51d was:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;Branch b1_4
Description: Inefficient object allocation for multi-stripe files
Details    : When selecting which OSTs to stripe files over, for files with
             a stripe count that divides evenly into the number of OSTs,
             the MDS is always picking the same starting OST for each file.
             Return the OST selection heuristic to the original design.

             Also make these variables per-LOV for the case of multiple
             MDTs on the same node and add sanity.sh test 51d to verify.
b=10671
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think a core problem with the test is that if the OSTs are imbalanced and QOS is used, then the starting OST allocation will also be imbalanced, causing the test to intermittently fail.  Either it should explicitly disable QOS before the start of the test (&lt;tt&gt;&amp;#42;.&amp;#42;.qos_threshold=100&lt;/tt&gt;, account for the OST imbalance, or just be more forgiving in the thresholds.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="310979" author="bzzz" created="Tue, 24 Aug 2021 14:31:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/6ff51064-1eac-40b4-997f-bc6fcf59607a&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/6ff51064-1eac-40b4-997f-bc6fcf59607a&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="243656" author="adilger" created="Mon, 11 Mar 2019 16:42:32 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Isn&apos;t this fallout from the previous patch &lt;a href=&quot;https://review.whamcloud.com/34386&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://review.whamcloud.com/34386&lt;/a&gt; &quot;&lt;tt&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-12055&quot; title=&quot;lod: ignore root layout if parent&amp;#39;s one includes pool&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-12055&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;LU-12055&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; lod: ignore root layout if parent&apos;s one includes pool&lt;/tt&gt;&quot; leaving the default &quot;-i 0&quot; striping on the whole filesystem?  I&apos;m not against fixing the test to not have assumptions about the test environment, but the other test should also be fixed not to change the global filesystem defaults in the middle of the test run. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="243648" author="gerrit" created="Mon, 11 Mar 2019 16:19:07 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Vladimir Saveliev (c17830@cray.com) uploaded a new patch: &lt;a href=&quot;https://review.whamcloud.com/34390&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://review.whamcloud.com/34390&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
